			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">You would use a similar counter to that used for the pulse 1 and pulse 2 channels, except it's 19 bits long.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">SSSS WDDD&nbsp; $FF22: Noise channel period and timbre<br />|||| ||||<br />|||| |+++- Mantissa of period (1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, or 14)<br />|||| +---- 0: hiss (32767-step sequence); 1: buzz (127-step sequence)<br />++++------ Exponent of period<br /></div><br /><br />Every noise clock (524288 Hz, I think; I don't have any 8-bit Game Boy dev tools to verify this, and my GBA tools are fairly packed away), subtract 1 from the noise channel's period counter. When the period counter becomes 0, load the period counter with (mantissa &lt;&lt; exponent) and clock the LFSR.<br /><br />If the timbre is set to buzz (W on), increasing values of mantissa (D) for any given exponent (S) will play the descending notes C, C, C, F, C, A flat, F, and D.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
